Preheat your #oven{} to 220°C/200°C fan/gas mark 7.

Pop a #large frying pan{} on medium-high heat (no oil).

Once hot, add the @British beef mince{240%grams} and fry until browned,
~{5-6%minutes}. Use a #spoon{} to break it up as it cooks, then drain and
discard any excess fat.

Season with @salt{} and @pepper{}. IMPORTANT: Wash your hands and equipment
after handling raw mince.

Meanwhile trim and coarsely grate the @carrot{1}(trimmed) (no need to peel).
Peel and grate the @garlic clove{2}(peeled and grated) (or use a garlic press).
Trim the @courgette{1}(trimmed) and slice into 1cm thick rounds.

Once the mince has browned, stir in the carrot. Cook until softened,
~{3-4%minutes}.

Once the carrot is soft, stir in the @tomato puree{30%grams},
@harissa paste{50%grams} (add less if you'd prefer things milder),
@ground cumin{1%sachet} and half the garlic. Lower the heat and stir-fry gently
until fragrant, ~{2-3%minutes}.

Add the @water{200%milliliters}(for the beef) and @chicken stock paste{10%grams}
to the pan.

Drain and rinse the @chickpeas{1%carton} in a #sieve{}, then add to the pan.

Season to taste with @salt{} and @pepper{}. Simmer, stirring occasionally,
until thickened, ~{10-12%minutes}. IMPORTANT: The mince is cooked when no
longer pink in the middle.

While the beef simmers, heat a large frying pan on high heat (no oil).

Once hot, add the courgette and cook until charred, ~{3-4%minutes}. Turn only
every couple of mins - this will result in the courgette picking up some
nice colour.

While the courgette chars, halve the @ciabatta{1} and pop it onto a #baking tray{},
cut-side up.

Spread over the remaining garlic and drizzle with the @olive oil{1%tbsp}(for the
garlic bread).

Bake on the top shelf of your oven until the edges are golden, ~{5-6%minutes}.

Taste and season the stew with @salt{} and @pepper{} if needed. Add a splash of
water if it's a little dry.

Share the stew between your #bowls{} and top with the charred courgettes.

Cut the garlic bread into triangles and serve alongside for dipping and
scooping. Enjoy!

